05615nam a22008295i 9780231548236DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018027032  a97802315482367 a10.7312/selc166482doi  a(DE-B1597)514673  a(OCoLC)1039210632  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aGE195 4aGE195b.S385 2018 7aPOL0480002bisacsh04a363.7/05262231 aSelcer, Perrin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Postwar Origins of the Global Environment :bHow the United Nations Built Spaceship Earth /cPerrin Selcer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b12 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Science, Global Governance, And The Environment -- t1. Behind The Burlap Curtain -- t2. Conserving The World Community -- t3. Men Against The Desert -- t4. The Soil Map Of The World And The Politics Of Scale -- t5. Locating The Global Environment -- t6. Spaceship Earth In The Age Of Fracture -- tConclusion. The View From A Utopia’S Ruins -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the Second World War, internationalists identified science as both the cause of and the solution to world crisis. Unless civilization learned to control the unprecedented powers science had unleashed, global catastrophe was imminent. But the internationalists found hope in the idea of world government. In The Postwar Origins of the Global Environment, Perrin Selcer argues that the metaphor of “Spaceship Earth”—the idea of the planet as a single interconnected system—exemplifies this moment, when a mix of anxiety and hope inspired visions of world community and the proliferation of international institutions.Selcer tells the story of how the United Nations built the international knowledge infrastructure that made the global-scale environment visible. Experts affiliated with UN agencies helped make the “global”—as in global population, global climate, and global economy—an object in need of governance. Selcer traces how UN programs such as UNESCO’s Arid Lands Project, the production of a soil map of the world, and plans for a global environmental-monitoring system fell short of utopian ambitions to cultivate world citizens but did produce an international community of experts with influential connections to national governments. He shows how events and personalities, cultures and ecologies, bureaucracies and ideologies, decolonization and the Cold War interacted to make global knowledge. A major contribution to global history, environmental history, and the history of development, this book relocates the origins of planetary environmentalism in the postwar politics of scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnvironmental policyxInternational cooperationxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnvironmentalismxInternational cooperationxHistoryy20th century. 0aInternationalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aSciencexInternational cooperationxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Intergovernmental Organizations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics and Social Sciences 2018 Engli